21":"0821","0843":"0843","0780":"0780","0815":"0815","0948":"0948","0805":"0805","0835":"0835","0825":"0825","0855":"0855","0900":"0900","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"0815–":"0815–Deceased","0805–0900":"0805–0900","0815–Male":"0815–Deceased","0835–0948":"0835–0948","0843–Female":"0843–Deceased","0855–Male":"0855–Deceased","0780–0825":"0780–0825","0821–Female":"0821–Deceased","0821":"0821","0843":"0843","0780":"0780","0815":"0815","0948":"0948","0805":"0805","0835":"0835","0825":"0825","0855":"0855","0900":"0900","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fras","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: rare variant of   Frey   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","English: from the personal name <i>Fray</i>, probably an Anglo-Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Fredo</i> (a pet form of names beginning with <i>Fred-</i> or <i>Freth-</i>), which was used by the Normans in Normandy.","English: nickname for a violent person, from Middle English <i>fray</i>, a shortened form of Middle English (Old French) <i>affrai</i> ‘attack, brawl, uproar’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frey","meanings":["Swiss German and German: status name for a free man, as opposed to a bondsman or serf, in the feudal system, from Middle High German <i>vrī</i> ‘free, independent’. This surname is also found in Hungary, Poland, and especially in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Free   and   Frei  .","English: variant of   Fray  .","History: This surname (see 1 above) is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Caradog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Respelling of <i>Caradog</i>, an ancient Celtic name apparently derived from the root <i>cār</i> ‘love’. This name was borne by a British chieftain of the 1st century  ad  in the Latinized form <i>Caractacus</i>, son of Cunobelinos."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Freich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: from a Low German form of   Friedrich  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Friedrich","meanings":["from <i>frid</i> ‘peace’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’; a royal and imperial name from an early date."]},{"name":"Frerichs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Arno, Franz, Fritz, Gerhard, Kurt, Reinhard.","North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Frerich  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Caradog Freich Fras ap Hywel was born in 0815, in Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Hywel Farf-fehinog ap Caradog, was 35 and his mother, Mrs Pasgen ap Urien Lord of Cydwell and all Gower, was -6. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"0815–":"0815–Surnud","0805–0900":"0805–0900","0815–Male":"0815–Surnud","0835–0948":"0835–0948","0843–Female":"0843–Surnud","0855–Male":"0855–Surnud","0780–0825":"0780–0825","0821–Female":"0821–Surnud","0821":"0821","0843":"0843","0780":"0780","0815":"0815","0948":"0948","0805":"0805","0835":"0835","0825":"0825","0855":"0855","0900":"0900","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"0815–":"0815–Kuollut","0805–0900":"0805–0900","0815–Male":"0815–Kuollut","0835–0948":"0835–0948","0843–Female":"0843–Kuollut","0855–Male":"0855–Kuollut","0780–0825":"0780–0825","0821–Female":"0821–Kuollut","0821":"0821","0843":"0843","0780":"0780","0815":"0815","0948":"0948","0805":"0805","0835":"0835","0825":"0825","0855":"0855","0900":"0900","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"0815–":"0815–Décédé","0805–0900":"0805–0900","0815–Male":"0815–Décédé","0835–0948":"0835–0948","0843–Female":"0843–Décédée","0855–Male":"0855–Décédé","0780–0825":"0780–0825","0821–Female":"0821–Dé